\description{
The Earth System Grid Federation (ESGF) is an international collaboration for
the software that powers most global climate change research, notably
assessments by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC).

The ESGF search service exposes RESTful APIs that can be used by clients to
query the contents of the underlying search index, and return results
matching the given constraints. The documentation of the APIs can be found
using this
\href{https://esgf.github.io/esg-search/ESGF_Search_RESTful_API.html}{link}.

\code{EsgQuery} is the workhorse for dealing with ESGF search services.
}
\note{
For bridge index nodes, only predefined common facets are returned.
\verb{$list_fields()} can be used to get all available fields,
including facets.
}
\section{\code{EsgQuery} object}{
\code{esg_query()} returns an \code{EsgQuery} object, which is an \link[R6:R6Class]{R6}
object with quite a few methods that can be classified into 3 categories:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Value listing}: methods to list all possible values of facets, fields,
shards, and values.
\item \strong{Parameter getter & setter}: methods to get the query parameter values or
set them before sending the actual query to the ESGF search services.
\item \strong{Query responses}: methods to collect results for the query response.
}
\subsection{Value listing}{

\code{EsgQuery} object provides the following value-listing methods to query
available facets, fields, shards, and values from the ESGF index node:
\itemize{
\item \href{#method-EsgQuery-list_facets}{\code{EsgQuery$list_facets()}}:
List all available facet names. When called, a
\href{https://esgf.github.io/esg-search/ESGF_Search_RESTful_API.html#facet-listings}{facet listing query}
is sent to the index node to get all available facets for the current
project (default: CMIP6).
\item \href{#method-EsgQuery-list_fields}{\code{EsgQuery$list_fields()}}:
List all available field names. This is useful for bridge index nodes
where facet listing is not available.
\item \href{#method-EsgQuery-list_shards}{\code{EsgQuery$list_shards()}}:
List all available shards (ESGF index nodes) that can be queried in
distributed searches.
\item \href{#method-EsgQuery-list_values}{\code{EsgQuery$list_values()}}:
List all available values of specific facets.
}
}

\subsection{Parameter getter & setter}{

The ESGF search services support a lot of parameters. The \code{EsgQuery}
contains dedicated methods to set values for most of them, including:
\itemize{
\item Most common keywords:
\href{#method-EsgQuery-facets}{\code{facets}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-offset}{\code{offset}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-limit}{\code{limit}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-fields}{\code{fields}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-type}{\code{type}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-replica}{\code{replica}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-latest}{\code{latest}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-distrib}{\code{distrib}}
and
\href{#method-EsgQuery-shards}{\code{shards}}.
\item Most common facets:
\href{#method-EsgQuery-project}{\code{project}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-activity_id}{\code{activity_id}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-experiment_id}{\code{experiment_id}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-source_id}{\code{source_id}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-variable_id}{\code{variable_id}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-frequency}{\code{frequency}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-variant_label}{\code{variant_label}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-date_range}{\code{date_range}},
\href{#method-EsgQuery-nominal_resolution}{\code{nominal_resolution}}
and
\href{#method-EsgQuery-data_node}{\code{data_node}}.
}

All methods act in a similar way:
\itemize{
\item If input is given, the corresponding parameter is set and the updated
\code{EsgQuery} object is returned.
\itemize{
\item This makes it possible to chain different parameter setters, e.g.
\code{EsgQuery$project("CMIP6")$frequency("day")$limit(1)} sets the parameter
\code{project}, \code{frequency} and \code{limit} sequentially.
\item For parameters that want character inputs, you can put a preceding \code{!} to
negate the constraints, e.g. \code{EsgQuery$project(!"CMIP6")} searches for
all projects except for \code{CMIP6}.
}
\item If no input is given, the current parameter value is returned. For example,
directly calling \code{EsgQuery$project()} returns the current value of the
\code{project} parameter. The returned value can be two types:
\itemize{
\item \code{NULL}, i.e. there is no constraint on the corresponding parameter
\item An \code{EsgQueryParam} object which is essentially a list of three elements:
\itemize{
\item \code{value}: The input values
\item \code{negate}: Whether there is a preceding \code{!} in the input
\item \code{name}: The parameter name
}
}
}

Despite methods for specific keywords and facets, you can specify arbitrary
query parameters using
\href{#method-EsgQuery-params}{\code{EsgQuery$params()}} method. For
details on the usage, please see the
\href{#method-EsgQuery-params}{documentation}.
}

\subsection{Query responses}{

The query is not sent unless related methods are called:
\itemize{
\item \href{#method-EsgQuery-count}{\code{EsgQuery$count()}}: Count the total
number of records that match the query.
\itemize{
\item You can return only the total number of matched record by calling
\code{EsgQuery$count(facets = FALSE)}
\item You can also count the matched records for specified facets, e.g.
\code{EsgQuery$count(facets = c("source_id", "activity_id"))}
}
\item \href{#method-EsgQuery-collect}{\code{EsgQuery$collect()}}: Collect the
query results and format it into an \link{EsgResultDataset} object.
}
}

\subsection{Bridge Index Nodes}{

Some ESGF index nodes are "bridge" nodes that have certain limitations
compared to standard index nodes. When using a bridge index node (e.g.,
\verb{https://esgf-node.ornl.gov/esgf-1-5-bridge}), the following restrictions
apply:
\itemize{
\item The \code{fields} parameter is not supported. All available fields are always
returned.
\item The \code{retracted} parameter is not supported and will be ignored.
\item Wget script generation is not supported. Calling \verb{$url(wget = TRUE)} will
result in an error.
\item Facet listing is not available. \verb{$list_facets()} will return a predefined
set of common facets instead. Use \verb{$list_fields()} to get all available
fields.
}
}

\subsection{Other helpers}{

\code{EsgQuery} object also provides several other helper functions:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Query URL generation}:
\itemize{
\item \href{#method-EsgQuery-url}{\code{EsgQuery$url()}}: Returns the actual
query URL or the wget script URL which can be used to download all files
matching the given constraints.
}
\item \strong{State persistence}:
\itemize{
\item \href{#method-EsgQuery-save}{\code{EsgQuery$save()}}: Save the query
state to a JSON file for later use.
\item \href{#method-EsgQuery-load}{\code{EsgQuery$load()}}: Restore the
query state from a JSON file created by \verb{$save()}.
}
\item \strong{Display}:
\itemize{
\item \href{#method-EsgQuery-print}{\code{EsgQuery$print()}}: Print a
summary of the current \code{EsgQuery} object including the index node URL,
the last query timestamp, and all query parameters.
}
}
}
}

